{"source_key":"sha256-903f1adf9377acdade8c215a48d8691f","record_index":158,"record_hash":"sha256:a40caa65b0e69e8eb71f36a49f94eb3cc961f62610f7beedb2c1dce4ecf2d9dd","timestamp":"2026-05-20T16:55:30.472Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 4f986a\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2141\nOutput:\ncapture observed. Capture timestamp and environment snapshot are capture turn\nattributes, not identity. This also makes retries easier: the same accepted\nrecord set maps to the same turn key.\n\nProvider-native turn identifiers should not define the durable `turn-key`.\nProviders may omit them, define turns differently, expose private/raw ids, or\ninclude many provider turns inside one first-time backfill capture. If present,\nthey can be stored as optional record-level grouping metadata, preferably as a\nsafe provider turn key rather than a raw provider id.\n\nMinimum useful fields:\n\n- capture turn id\n- session key\n- source key\n- capture kind\n- capture timestamp\n- transcript record membership, probably by record hash and/or source record\n  index\n- optional provider turn key on transcript records, for grouping/display only\n- previous turn reference, when there is a previous capture turn in the same\n  session\n- environment snapshot\n\nThe record membership matters because `but-agentlog` already deduplicates\nrecords. Without turn membership, repeated hook capture preserves the transcript\nbut erases the boundaries between capture invocations.\n\n`TurnDetail.records` must be an ordered array. That order is authoritative for\nrendering records within a capture turn; hashes and source indexes identify the\nrecords, but they are not a replacement for sequence.\n\nThe model should distinguish:\n\n- **capture turn:** a stop-hook capture observation with new transcript records\n  and a repository environment snapshot\n- **provider turn:** a provider-native conversation grouping, such as a user\n  prompt and the resulting assistant/tool activity\n\nCapture turns are the durable agentlog concept. Provider turns are useful for UI\ngrouping when available, but they are not portable enough to define the storage\nmodel across agents.\n\nStore `previous_turn_key` as a session-wide previous capture turn pointer when\nit is available. It is not part\n[TRUNCATED]\nnch id when the workspace snapshot exposes a\n  durable id, otherwise normalized full refname when available, with display\n  name kept separately for UI\n- review key material: strongest available review identity, for example\n  `github-pr:owner/repo#1284`, `pull-request:<remote-url-hash>#1284`, or\n  `gitbutler-review:<review-id>`\n- change key material: canonical bytes/text for the GitButler change id\n\nHash branch, review, and change key material before embedding it in GitMeta key\nnames. Keep the readable canonical value in `observed_targets` and the\nenvironment snapshot.\n\nFor worktree file paths, store relative paths plainly on the capture turn\nsnapshot. They are useful handoff context and keep explanations understandable.\nGuard against pathological cases such as generated trees, vendor drops, or giant\nlockfile-driven changes by storing a count and truncated flag alongside a capped\nsorted path list.\n\nUse a path cap of 256 entries per path list. Keep the total count even when the\nlist is not truncated. It is redundant in the common case, but useful for\nconsistent reads and essential when `*_truncated = true`.\n\nExample worktree shape:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"files\": [\"src/foo.rs\", \"src/bar.rs\"],\n  \"file_count\": 2,\n  \"files_truncated\": false\n}\n```\n\nDo not store per-commit file lists in the primitive layer. They were useful for\nearly scoring sketches, but they add capture-time cost and storage volume before\nwe have a product consumer. A review or handoff feature can derive richer\ncommit/path evidence later if the UX needs it.\n\nDo not store commit message summaries in the capture turn snapshot. Commit\nsubjects can be read from Git by `commit_id` when a UI needs them, and they are\nnot useful association evidence.\n\nSnapshot status values:\n\n- `complete`: worktree and stack/branch observations were collected\n- `partial`: some observations were collected but one or more optional pieces\n  failed\n- `failed`: no useful environment observation was collected\n\nFor failed or partial snapshots, store a coarse `error_kind` if useful for\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T16:55:30.472Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}